{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8b5c9ccd-4145-44d9-8cd8-f1d1da9809e3","content":"This repository doesn't contain documentation on that topic. However, here's the general guidance for macOS:\n\n**Recovering a crash dump on macOS without `createdump`:**\n\n1. **Check Apple's crash reports** — macOS automatically writes crash logs to:\n   - `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n   - `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n\n   Look for a `.ips` or `.crash` file matching your process name and timestamp.\n\n2. **Enable core dumps** before reproducing:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   sudo sysctl kern.corefile=/tmp/core.%P\n   ```\n   Then re-run your app. The core file will appear at `/tmp/core.<pid>`.\n\n3. **Use `lldb`** to analyze the core dump:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /tmp/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n\n4. **If SIP blocks core dumps**, you may need to:\n   - Run from a non-SIP-protected directory\n   - Or temporarily adjust SIP settings (requires recovery mode)\n\n5. **For NativeAOT specifically**, ensure you published with debug symbols (`-p:StripSymbols=false`) so `lldb` can resolve managed frames via the `.dsym` bundle.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4e4c636b-61f3-4931-9e1b-d060c5155969","outputTokens":316},"id":"5022a57a-a94e-4afe-b724-39a8ca10b73d","timestamp":"2026-04-03T01:02:35.841Z","parentId":"3615ea2d-a68b-4efc-83e3-3f6e80a8a0cb"}
